<span id="freeTextContainer7016565608697959307">I thought I&apos;d finally start the Harry Bosch series as it&apos;s always highly regarded, The Black Echo is such a great introduction for the LAPD Homicide Detective.<br/><br/>The novel opens with a normal run of the mill murder investigaton as a body is discovered off Mulholland Drive, once Bouch realises that he knows the victim as Billy Meadows from their time together during the Vietnam War the plot really kicks into gear.<br/><br/>It&apos;s such a smart way to learn of Harry&apos;s past as he recounts the experiences of being </span>
  <span id="freeText7016565608697959307" style="display:none">I thought I'd finally start the Harry Bosch series as it's always highly regarded, The Black Echo is such a great introduction for the LAPD Homicide Detective.<br /><br />The novel opens with a normal run of the mill murder investigaton as a body is discovered off Mulholland Drive, once Bouch realises that he knows the victim as Billy Meadows from their time together during the Vietnam War the plot really kicks into gear.<br /><br />It's such a smart way to learn of Harry's past as he recounts the experiences of being a 'tunnel rat' and how the horrors and isolation has affected him.<br /><br />The story takes place during the end of May, with each part covering an individual day.<br />Even though each section is long it's easy to get draw into the mystery, it was only seeing the page count jump that I happened to notice.<br /><br />A really strong and accomplished debut.<br /><br /></span>
