<div id="review_1008320190" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1008320190" />
    <a title="Mona" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7020601-mona"><img alt="Mona" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1392557851p2/7020601.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1008320190?book_show_action=true">Jul 27, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mona" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mona" href="/user/show/7020601-mona">Mona</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audio CD 9781423323266" href="/book/show/49344.The_Black_Echo">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1008320190" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2241992260916039203"><b>Enjoyable Well Written Crime Novel, Except for the Last Part of the Book </b><br/><br/>As another reviewer, Suzy, says, this novel is very &quot;old school&quot;. <a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/888499978?book_show_action=false&amp;page=1'>https://www.goodreads.com/review/show...</a><br/><br/>A lot of it may resonate more with those of us old enough to remember pay phones, Alice&apos;s Restaurant, and the Viet Nam War and its aftermath.<br/><br/>Still, except for the ending, which I found somehow unsatisfying, this is well written enough to carry any reader, whether or not they remember its era.<br/><br/>This is my first Michael Con</span>
  <span id="freeText2241992260916039203" style="display:none"><b>Enjoyable Well Written Crime Novel, Except for the Last Part of the Book </b><br /><br />As another reviewer, Suzy, says, this novel is very "old school". <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/888499978?book_show_action=false&amp;page=1">https://www.goodreads.com/review/show...</a><br /><br />A lot of it may resonate more with those of us old enough to remember pay phones, Alice's Restaurant, and the Viet Nam War and its aftermath.<br /><br />Still, except for the ending, which I found somehow unsatisfying, this is well written enough to carry any reader, whether or not they remember its era.<br /><br />This is my first Michael Connolly novel, and I'll certainly be reading more. His background as a journalist shows here. He knows what he's writing about from first hand experience. His writing is clear and based in facts.<br /><br />Harry Bosch (who's real name is, hilariously, Hieronymous Bosch, after the fifteenth century Dutch mystical/fantastical painter who was way ahead of his time), is a maverick LAPD detective. He is extremely good at his job, which involves investigating murders. He's not good at playing the phony political games demanded by the LAPD. They keep him around because he's a terrific detective. But he's frequently in trouble with the brass, who are constantly bullying him (and many of his coworkers). Bosch is an interesting character, even though he's a "type" in crime novels---the loner who doesn't fit in, haunted by his own past. <br /><br />Harry was a "tunnel rat" in Viet Nam. This means he went into the tunnels to smoke out the Viet Cong hiding there (often with explosives). His experiences in Nam have left him with lifelong PTSD and insomnia.<br /><br />A dead body turns up in a pipe near West Hollywood. The dead person turns out to be Billy Meadows, a man Harry did "tunnel rat" duty with in Viet Nam.<br /><br />Harry gets dragged into the investigation. Even the FBI gets involved. He ends up partnering with enigmatic and lovely FBI agent Eleanor Wish in the investigation.<br /><br />Things quickly spiral out of control. There is all kinds of collateral damage from this murder and its investigation. Harry is being tailed by two goons from Internal Affairs in the LAPD, since they clearly don't trust him.<br /><br />I can't say much more about the story without giving spoilers.<br /><br />The LAPD brass are depicted as phony, corrupt, lying, self-serving bullies with zero interest in the people that work for them. Since I was a long time worker in the corporate world, this rings quite true to me. They hate Harry because he's way smarter than they are, stands up to them, and (usually) tells the truth. He also smart mouths them in a way that isn't very diplomatic. They keep saying he's "not part of the LAPD family". Connolly's portrait of management generally holds true of corporate management as well, although they are less heavy handed than the LAPD honchos.<br /><br />I guessed a few of the reveals at the end, but not all of them.<br /><br />There was something anti-climactic and unsatisfactory about the ending, as if it were tacked on as an afterthought.<br /><br />Too bad, because this book had me until the last quarter of the novel.<br /><br />Dick Hill wasn't bad as a narrator, except that he kept giving LAPD cops heavy Boston accents, which seemed very out of place.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2241992260916039203" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


