  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3475053282" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3475053282" />
    <a title="Matt" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16077597-matt"><img alt="Matt" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1582900704p2/16077597.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3475053282?book_show_action=true">Sep 16, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matt" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matt" href="/user/show/16077597-matt">Matt</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/41794251-the-black-echo">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3475053282" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7077843324215357331">I loved my first Harry Bosch thriller!<br/><br/>In this first case Bosch is confronted with a one-pipe-problem: After an anonymous wit call, a DB is discovered, stuck in a drain pipe up at Lake Hollywood. It turns out Bosch knew the victim (who was <em>stiff as a wedding night prick</em>, according to some other cop) twenty years before from the time when they both served as so called tunnel rats during the Vietnam war, chasing &amp; smoking out the VC from their chthonic hideouts. During the course of his investigati</span>
  <span id="freeText7077843324215357331" style="display:none">I loved my first Harry Bosch thriller!<br><br>In this first case Bosch is confronted with a one-pipe-problem: After an anonymous wit call, a DB is discovered, stuck in a drain pipe up at Lake Hollywood. It turns out Bosch knew the victim (who was <em>stiff as a wedding night prick</em>, according to some other cop) twenty years before from the time when they both served as so called tunnel rats during the Vietnam war, chasing &amp; smoking out the VC from their chthonic hideouts. During the course of his investigation the LAPD homicide cop is teaming up with an enigmatic &amp; enticing female FBI agent who is hoping to solve another case from a while back, which might be connected to the current murder.<br><br>IMO the novel is even better than the streaming series on Amazon, although I binge-watched that one, too, a couple months ago with increasing enjoyment, after Stephen King has made <a href="https://twitter.com/StephenKing/status/1259999105637638145" rel="nofollow noopener">a recommendation on Twitter</a>.<br><br>In contrast to the series the book is set around the time it was published, early 1990s, which gives the reading a certain kind of nostalgic charm. For instance there are no cell phones available, the computers are not very sophisticated and still have to share their place in the offices with typewriters and stuff. Cops are alerted by good old fashioned “pagers” to which they can usually reply using a “pay phone” on the street. Connelly seems keen to highlight the technological advances of the time. Sometimes this comes out unintentionally funny, like when a computer (an IBM PC) produces the result of a query after only 30 seconds, for which today’s machines would take a few milliseconds at worst. <br><br>The main character is drawn out pretty well, and has more depth than the TV character, although Titus Welliver does a very fine job here as well. Bosch’s background is revealed little by little and it’s fun to watch. In a little afterword Connelly explains about the origins of the Bosch character, and why and how he, Connelly, got to writing crime fiction in the first place.<br><br>Also, the number of characters in the book is quite manageable, and they are easily distinguishable, which is something I cannot say about other books from this genre. The author likes to give characters some quirky names: For example, Harry Bosch’s first name is actually Hieronymus (<em>rhymes with anonymous</em>), a name his mother gave him after the famous 15th century Dutch painter. The female FBI agent’s name is Wish (as in “careful what you — for”, perhaps?). There are two IAD cops trailing Bosch and they are called Lewis &amp; Clark (always being on an expedition) and then there’s DC Irvin Irving (<em>[whose] one impediment as a Los Angeles policeman [is] his silly name</em>).<br><br>The story is comprehensible &amp; coherent and the plot has no holes in it (as far as I could see), and it progresses at a comfortable pace for me (YMMV), dragging on a little at times, and has some repetitions, but they are not really annoying. All in all I’m quite satisfied with this one.<br><br>One down, 24 (and counting) to go!<br><br><br>PS. If you find some acronyms above that you’re not familiar with, don’t worry &amp; welcome to the club. I had to figure them out myself. It’s mostly cop lingo that you einevitably will learn while reading.<br><br><br><a href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/" rel="nofollow noopener">
  <img alt="Creative Commons License" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1380148217i/680962.png" class="gr-hostedUserImg">
</a><br>This work is licensed under a <a href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/" rel="nofollow noopener">Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 3.0 Unported License</a>.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7077843324215357331" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


